    gospel_ref: 'John 20:19-23',
    gospel_text: 'On the evening of that day, the first day of the week, the doors being shut where the disciples were, for fear of the Jews, Jesus came and stood among them and said to them, "Peace be with you." When he had said this, he showed them his hands and his side... Jesus said to them again, "Peace be with you. As the Father has sent me, even so I send you." And when he had said this, he breathed on them, and said to them, "Receive the Holy Spirit. If you forgive the sins of any, they are forgiven; if you retain the sins of any, they are retained."',
    reflection: 'Pentecost is the birthday of the Church. Fifty days after Easter, the Holy Spirit descends in wind and tongues of fire and the timid apostles become bold preachers who turn the world upside down. Three thousand are baptized in a single day. The Spirit who hovered over the waters at Creation now hovers over a new creation: the Church. And the same Spirit was given to YOU at Baptism, sealed at Confirmation. He is not a memory of an ancient event. He lives in your soul. The same power that raised Jesus from the dead is in you (Romans 8:11). The question is not whether you have the Holy Spirit. The question is whether you are letting Him work.',
